🧠 SwiftUI Memory Management & Retain Cycles (Day 2)

SwiftUI removes much of UIKit’s lifecycle complexity, but memory management issues still exist.

Common problems include:

Retain cycles in closures

Long-lived ObservableObjects

Tasks that never cancel

Incorrect state ownership

Understanding these prevents memory leaks and zombie view models.

1️⃣ SwiftUI Views Are Value Types

SwiftUI views are structs.

struct ProfileView: View {
    var body: some View {
        Text("Hello")
    }
}

Because views are value types, they are:

Cheap to recreate

Not retained like UIKit controllers

Not responsible for memory leaks

Memory issues usually come from reference types.

2️⃣ ViewModels Are Reference Types

ViewModels are typically classes.

final class ProfileViewModel: ObservableObject {
    @Published var name = "Deepak"
}

These objects:

Persist in memory

Can create retain cycles

Must be owned carefully

This is why @StateObject exists.

3️⃣ Using the Wrong Property Wrapper
❌ Memory Bug
@ObservedObject var vm = ProfileViewModel()

This recreates the ViewModel repeatedly.

It may also lead to unexpected retention patterns.

✅ Correct Ownership
@StateObject var vm = ProfileViewModel()

Now the ViewModel lifecycle matches the view identity.

4️⃣ Retain Cycles in Closures

Swift closures capture self strongly by default.

❌ Retain Cycle
class ViewModel {

    func load() {
        service.fetch { result in
            self.process(result)
        }
    }
}

If service retains the closure, the ViewModel never deallocates.

✅ Correct
service.fetch { [weak self] result in
    self?.process(result)
}

This breaks the retain cycle.

5️⃣ Retain Cycles in Combine

Combine pipelines can retain ViewModels.

❌
publisher
    .sink { value in
        self.handle(value)
    }
    .store(in: &cancellables)
✅
publisher
    .sink { [weak self] value in
        self?.handle(value)
    }
    .store(in: &cancellables)
6️⃣ Tasks That Never Cancel

Swift concurrency introduces another memory trap.

❌
Task {
    await loadData()
}

If the view disappears, the task may continue running.

✅

Use .task in SwiftUI.

.task {
    await loadData()
}

SwiftUI cancels the task automatically when the view disappears.

7️⃣ Long-Lived EnvironmentObjects

EnvironmentObject can accidentally become global singletons.

❌
.environmentObject(AppState())

If AppState grows large, it causes:

global invalidations

unnecessary view updates

high memory retention

✅

Split global state into smaller models.

Example:

AuthState
UserSettings
ThemeState
8️⃣ Detecting Memory Leaks

Use Xcode tools:

Instruments
Leaks
Allocations
Debug Memory Graph
Debug → View Memory Graph

This reveals retain cycles instantly.

9️⃣ Debugging Deallocation

Add deinit logs.

deinit {
    print("ProfileViewModel deallocated")
}

If this never prints, something is retaining it.

🔥 Common SwiftUI Memory Mistakes

Strong closure captures

Combine pipelines without weak references

Long-running Tasks

Massive EnvironmentObjects

Incorrect ViewModel ownership

🧠 Interview Power Answer

If asked:

“Do SwiftUI apps still have memory leaks?”

Answer:

“Yes — but they usually come from reference types like ViewModels, Combine pipelines, or async tasks. SwiftUI views themselves are value types and rarely cause leaks.”

⭐ Golden Memory Rules

Views are value types

ViewModels must be owned with StateObject

Always weak-capture in closures

Cancel long tasks

Monitor EnvironmentObject size
